
This directory is intended for PlatformIO Test Runner and project tests.

Unit Testing is a software testing method by which individual units of
source code, sets of one or more MCU program modules together with associated
control data, usage procedures, and operating procedures, are tested to
determine whether they are fit for use. Unit testing finds problems early
in the development cycle.

More information about PlatformIO Unit Testing:
- https://docs.platformio.org/en/latest/advanced/unit-testing/index.html

## Feature checklist:

    ✅ 8-voice polyphony (extensible to 16)
    ✅ Dual VCO with saw/tri/square + shape modifier
    ✅ SVF lowpass filter with drive and key tracking
    ✅ Amp + Mod envelopes (ADSR)
    ✅ LFO (5 shapes, 4 destinations)
    ✅ Portamento
    ✅ Pitch bend (±2 semitones)
    ✅ Master bus FX (chorus + delay + reverb)
    ✅ USB + DIN MIDI
    ✅ Touch UI with tabbed pages and tap-select/drag-adjust
    ✅ SD patch storage (128 slots)
    ✅ Click-free parameter changes

## What to Test

- LFO — set LFO_RATE to ~2 Hz, LFO_DEPTH to 50%, destination CUTOFF. Hold a note; filter should wobble.
- Portamento — turn up P_PORTAMENTO past 20%. Play ascending notes legato; pitch should glide.
- Pitch bend — move your controller's wheel; notes should bend ±2 semitones smoothly.
- Chorus — crank FX_MOD_DEPTH. Signal should widen and shimmer.
- Delay — DLY_MIX to 30%, DLY_TIME to 250ms, DLY_FB to 40%. Classic ping-pong echo.
- Reverb — REV_MIX to 40%, REV_SIZE to 60%. Sustained notes should bloom with tail.
- Patch load click test — design a patch with full resonance and ~90% cutoff. Save. Go to a different patch with minimum cutoff. Load back and forth. There should be no audible clicks — just a ~15 ms sweep.

## Suggested Enhancements (Your Call)

A few directions you might want to take this further:

- Noise generator + "Multi" oscillator — Prologue's multi-engine has noise, VPM (phase modulation), and user oscillators. A simple white noise + FM pair would round out the mixer.
- Unison/Detune voice mode — stacks all voices on one note with detuning for fat leads.
- Hardware encoders — when you're ready to add them, I can show you an efficient interrupt-driven reader that ties directly into the same Synth::setParam plumbing the touch UI uses.
- Patch name editor — on-screen keyboard for naming patches before save.
- MIDI learn — tap a knob, wiggle a controller, CC gets bound to that parameter.
